/*
DEEP COPY AND SHALLOW COPY

EX 1=>  const a = { x: 10 };
const b = a;
b.x = 20;
console.log(a.x);

👉 Answer: 20

👉 Why?
b is not a copy. It points to the same memory as a.

EX2=>
    const a = {
  name: "Agraj",
  address: { city: "Delhi" }
};

const b = { ...a };

b.address.city = "Mumbai";

console.log(a.address.city);

Answer: Mumbai

By writing address: { ...a.address }, you are explicitly telling JavaScript:
Create a new object for the address property.
Copy the properties from a.address into this new object.



